# Cyrius — Tooling & Formats
# Compiler binaries, CLI driver, dev tools, helper scripts,
# format files, env vars, flags, plugin/LSP wiring.
# Refreshed 2026-06-08 at v6.1.11 (full vidya-refresh pass): the pending
# cc5→cycc / cyrc→cybs name purge applied across all entries (the "cyc"
# misprediction corrected to cycc); compiler_flags + compiler_env_vars
# gained the TS modes (--lex-ts/--parse-ts/--emit-js), --pie/CYRIUS_PIE,
# and CYRIUS_JSX_PRAGMA. Prior: 2026-06-07 at v6.0.87 (compiler_binaries
# entry — names/bootstrap-chain/sizes).
# 15 entries.

[[entries]]
name = "compiler_binaries"
description = "cycc + cross-compilers (aarch64 Linux/Mach-O, Windows PE, cyrius-x bytecode)"
category = "cyrius"
---
The Cyrius toolchain ships multiple compiler binaries, each
targeting a different host/output triple. All bootstrap from the
same 29 KB seed (`bootstrap/asm`): seed → cybs → cycc (the
cyrc→cybs + cc5→cycc rename landed v6.0.0; the bridge retired v5.11.66).

== PRIMARY (Linux x86_64 self-host) ==

  `cycc`             — main compiler, ~1.0 MB (1,036,848 B) at v6.1.11.
                       Reads .cyr source on stdin; writes ELF executable
                       on stdout. Self-hosts byte-identical via
                       two-step + three-step verify.

== CROSSES ==

  `cycc_aarch64`     — Linux ARM64 + macOS Mach-O ARM64 cross.
                       ~593 KB (593,384 B) at v6.1.11. Built from
                       `src/main_aarch64.cyr`. Apple Silicon also
                       self-hosts byte-identically via
                       `src/main_aarch64_native.cyr` (the native fork
                       gained the auto-call-main port at v6.0.68; the
                       aarch64 ESYSXLAT gained stat/rename/symlink at
                       v6.0.68, §D1).
  `cycc_win` (cross) — Windows PE32+ cross. ~806 KB (805,888 B) at
                       v6.1.11. Native self-host via `cycc_win.exe` on
                       Windows 11 since v5.5.10 (byte-identical to
                       Linux cross output). Built from
                       `src/main_win.cyr`. Multi-DLL imports (kernel32
                       + shell32 + dxgi) + compiler-emitted indirect
                       calls (callptr) since v6.0.69-.70.
  `cycc_macho`       — Mach-O x86_64 cross (Intel Mac).
  `cycc_macho_arm`   — Mach-O aarch64 cross (built when not
                       producing native via cycc_aarch64 on macOS).
                       Built from `src/main_aarch64_macho.cyr`.
  `cycc_cx`          — cyrius-x bytecode entry (`CYX\\0` magic +
                       opcodes; v5.7.12 path B). Built from
                       `src/main_cx.cyr`. Re-validated each minor
                       via `tests/regression-cx-roundtrip.sh`.

== RENAME PIN ==

cc3 → cc5 at v5.0.0 was the last name-change penalty paid.
cc5 → cycc + cyrc → cybs at v6.0.0 is the FINAL rename — cycc
stays cycc forever (no cycc6 at v7.0.0, no cycc7 at v8.0.0;
"cyc" was a pre-cut misprediction — the real name is cycc).
`VERSION` file + `--version` output are the only sources of
truth for which release a binary is.

== STANDALONE TOOLS (per `[release].bins` in cyrius.cyml) ==

  `cyrius`              CLI driver — delegates to cycc + helpers.
  `cyrfmt`              Source formatter (analogous to gofmt).
  `cyrlint`             Static analyzer (warnings + dead-code).
  `cyrdoc`              Doc generator (HTML + markdown emit).
  `cybs`                Bootstrap compiler (seed → cybs → cycc;
                        formerly `cyrc`. The separate `bridge.cyr`
                        intermediate was retired at v5.11.66).
  `ark`                 Package manager (.ark distributables).
  `cyrld`               Linker (cyrius-native static linking).
  `cyrius_api_surface`  Public API snapshot diff (v5.7.33).
  `cyrius-lsp`          Language Server Protocol implementation.
  `cyriusly`            Toolchain-version management CLI (v5.11.10
                        — native cyrius port of scripts/cyriusly;
                        11 verbs: version / list / ls / which / home /
                        help / use / install / uninstall / update /
                        setup / cmdtools).
  `ts_test_runner`      TypeScript-frontend test harness (v5.11.11
                        — walks .ts/.tsx fixtures via cycc --parse-ts /
                        --lex-ts). Real-corpus smoke against
                        secureyeoman: 2053/2053 .ts + 435/435 .tsx
                        pass at --mode=parse.

[[entries]]
name = "cyrius_cli"
description = "cyrius — top-level CLI driver. Orchestrates cycc + auto-deps + standalone tools across build/test/quality/info verbs."
category = "cyrius"
---
`cyrius` is the user-facing entry point. It auto-resolves
`[deps.*]` declared in `cyrius.cyml` before any
build/run/test/bench/fuzz/check/soak/smoke command (v5.7.21
added the auto-prepend for fuzz; check folded in by v5.7.50).

== BUILD VERBS ==

  cyrius build [--aarch64] [--no-deps] [--strict-pin] [-D NAME] <src> <out>
  cyrius run [--aarch64] <source.cyr>
  cyrius test [--aarch64] <test.cyr>          — exit 0 = pass
  cyrius bench <bench.cyr>
  cyrius check [--with-deps] <src.cyr>        — syntax-only
  cyrius self                                 — cycc==cycc byte-identical
  cyrius clean                                — wipe build/
  cyrius lib sync [--dry-run]                 — copy snapshot lib/*.cyr → ./lib/ (v5.11.58)

`-D NAME` injects `#define NAME` at the top of the bundled
source (preprocessor-style; useful for feature flags). The
`-D` family was added during the v5.6.x optimization arc.

`--strict-pin` (v5.11.58) augments the cycc child's envp with
`CYRIUS_STRICT_PIN=1`, which v5.11.57's `_check_cyml_pin_drift`
in lex.cyr reads to upgrade the pin-drift warning to a hard
exit (code 1). CI gating path for pin-faithful builds — fail
loudly when cwd's `cyrius.cyml [package].cyrius` pin doesn't
match cycc's compile-time version.

`lib sync` (v5.11.58) copies `~/.cyrius/versions/<X>/lib/*.cyr`
into `./lib/`, where `<X>` = cyml pin or wrapper version.
Third remediation for the shadow-lib warning (besides "delete
./lib/" and `CYRIUS_NO_WARN_SHADOW_LIB=1`).

== PROJECT VERBS ==

  cyrius init <name>                          — scaffold new project
  cyrius package                              — emit .ark distributable
  cyrius publish                              — push to ark registry
  cyrius port <rust-project>                  — Rust → Cyrius scaffold
  cyrius install <pkg>                        — fetch binary release
  cyrius update                               — re-resolve deps to latest tags
  cyrius deps [--no-lock|--verify]            — manifest-driven dep resolve

== QUALITY VERBS ==

  cyrius fmt <file.cyr> [--check]
  cyrius lint <file.cyr>
  cyrius doc [--check] <file.cyr>             — also: --serve [port]
  cyrius vet <source.cyr>                     — include-graph audit
  cyrius deny <source.cyr>                    — project-policy enforcement
  cyrius audit                                — full sweep: self-host + test + fmt + lint
  cyrius distlib <profile>                    — produce dist-shape stdlib
  cyrius capacity [--check|--json] <src.cyr>  — frame/heap/code measurement
  cyrius api-surface [--update]               — public-API snapshot diff (v5.7.33)

== TESTING VERBS ==

  cyrius test                                 — auto-discovers tests/tcyr/*.tcyr
  cyrius bench                                — auto-discovers benches/*.bcyr
  cyrius fuzz                                 — auto-discovers fuzz/*.fcyr
  cyrius soak [N]                             — N-iter self-host loop + tests/scyr/*.scyr
  cyrius smoke                                — auto-discovers tests/smcyr/*.smcyr
  cyrius coverage                             — per-fn coverage report
  cyrius doctest <file.cyr>                   — run `# example:` blocks

== INFO + LSP ==

  cyrius lsp                                  — build + install cyrius-lsp
  cyrius version                              — toolchain version (+ manifest-pin line in projects, v5.11.58)
  cyrius version --project                    — project's VERSION file
  cyrius which                                — path to cycc
  cyrius repl                                 — expression REPL
  cyrius help                                 — full verb list

== --version BEHAVIOR (v5.11.58) ==

When `cyrius --version` runs inside a project tree (cwd has
`cyrius.cyml` with `[package].cyrius = "X.Y.Z"`), the output
appends a second line:

  cyrius 5.11.57
  manifest-pin: 5.11.55 (drift — wrapper is 5.11.57)

The `(drift — wrapper is X.Y.Z)` suffix only appears on
mismatch; clean match prints just `manifest-pin: 5.11.55`. The
drift surface helps consumers spot toolchain skew the moment
they check the wrapper, before the cycc pin-drift warning fires
during a build.

CROSS-REF: see `compiler_env_vars` for `CYRIUS_STRICT_PIN` +
`CYRIUS_NO_WARN_PIN_DRIFT` env knobs (cycc-side, v5.11.57).

[[entries]]
name = "tcyr_test_format"
description = ".tcyr — assertion-driven test format with auto-discovery"
category = "cyrius"
---
`.tcyr` files are runnable Cyrius programs that follow the
test-runner contract. `cyrius test` (no args) auto-discovers
`tests/tcyr/*.tcyr` and runs each; positional arg compiles +
runs a specific file.

Standard shape:

    include "lib/string.cyr"
    include "lib/syscalls.cyr"
    include "lib/alloc.cyr"
    include "lib/assert.cyr"

    alloc_init();

    test_group("widget basics");
    assert_eq(widget_size(), 16, "widget is 16 bytes");
    assert_eq(widget_id(0), 0, "ids start at 0");

    var r = assert_summary();
    syscall(60, r);   # exit 0 = all pass; non-zero = failure count

`cyrius test` auto-prepends every dep distfile + the
`[deps].stdlib` list from `cyrius.cyml` so the runner doesn't
need to write include directives for stdlib in scope.

Output convention:
  `=== <test_group name> ===`
  `  PASS: <assertion msg>`  (only on --verbose; default is silent on pass)
  `  FAIL: <assertion msg> (got X, expected Y)`
  Final line: `N passed, M failed (T total)`

[[entries]]
name = "bcyr_fcyr_scyr_smcyr_formats"
description = ".bcyr (bench) / .fcyr (fuzz) / .scyr (soak) / .smcyr (smoke) — test-adjacent harness formats"
category = "cyrius"
---
Four sibling formats to .tcyr, each scoped to a specific
validation cadence.

== .bcyr — BENCH HARNESS ==

`cyrius bench` auto-discovers `benches/*.bcyr`. Same source-
shape as .tcyr but uses `lib/bench.cyr`'s timing helpers:

    bench_start("op_name");
    ... work ...
    bench_end("op_name");
    bench_report();

For sub-microsecond ops where `clock_gettime` overhead dominates:

    bench_batch_start("hot_op", 1000000);   # 1M iterations
    var i = 0; while (i < 1000000) { ...; i = i + 1; }
    bench_batch_stop();

`bench-history.sh` (in vidya) snapshots `cyrius bench` per-commit
for historical regression diff.

== .fcyr — FUZZ HARNESS ==

`cyrius fuzz` auto-discovers `fuzz/*.fcyr`. Each harness exercises
a module with stress patterns. Exit 0 = pass, non-0 = fail,
139 = SIGSEGV crash. Standard fuzz harnesses ship with stdlib:
`hashmap.fcyr`, `vec.fcyr`, `string.fcyr`, `freelist.fcyr`.

`cyrius fuzz --compiler [N]` runs mutation fuzzing against cycc
itself (separate from project-level harnesses).

== .scyr — SOAK HARNESS ==

`cyrius soak [N]` runs N iterations of the full validation loop
plus walks `tests/scyr/*.scyr`. Long-running validation —
overnight loops. Catches: non-determinism, memory leaks, state
corruption, codegen drift.

  cyrius soak 100                  # quick overnight
  cyrius soak 1000                 # full soak
  cyrius soak 10 "repo1 repo2"     # custom downstream-repo list

Example: `tests/scyr/alloc_pressure.scyr`.

== .smcyr — SMOKE HARNESS ==

`cyrius smoke` auto-discovers `tests/smcyr/*.smcyr`. Quick sanity
checks — meant to run in seconds, gate releases. Example:
`tests/smcyr/compile_minimal.smcyr`.

[[entries]]
name = "cyml_format"
description = "CYML (.cyml) — TOML header + markdown body in one file. Used by vidya, cyrius.cyml, this-very-file."
category = "cyrius"
---
CYML — Cyrius Markup Language — is TOML above the delimiter,
markdown below it. Implemented in `lib/cyml.cyr`.

== THE PROBLEM IT SOLVES ==

Three formats in the AGNOS ecosystem each solved half:
  - TOML: typed fields, but prose in triple-quoted strings is ugly
  - Markdown: agents read it natively, but no type system
  - YAML frontmatter: hybrid that works, but YAML brings known
    bugs (indentation-sensitive, Norway problem, implicit typing)

CYML is the deliberate fourth option: TOML on top, markdown
underneath, `---` separator.

== SHAPES ==

Single-entry:

    [meta]
    name = "example"
    tags = ["tutorial"]

    ---

    Everything below the delimiter is markdown.
    Full prose. Code blocks. Lists. No escaping.

Multi-entry (vidya pattern; this file is the canonical example):

    [topic]
    id = "tooling"

    [[entries]]
    name = "first_entry"
    type = "best_practice"

    ---

    First entry's markdown body.

    [[entries]]
    name = "second_entry"
    type = "gotcha"

    ---

    Second entry's body.

== PARSE RULES ==

  1. File starts in TOML mode.
  2. `[[entries]]` on its own line starts a new entry TOML header.
  3. `---` on its own line switches to markdown body.
  4. Next `[[entries]]` or EOF ends the current body.
  5. TOML above the first `[[entries]]` is file-level metadata.
  6. Leading/trailing whitespace on body is trimmed.
  7. Body is stored as raw string — no markdown parsing on the
     library side; the consumer can run a markdown parser if
     they want HTML output.

== API ==

    var doc = cyml_parse(data, len);
    var n = cyml_doc_entry_count(doc);
    var e = cyml_doc_entry(doc, 0);
    var hdr = cyml_entry_header(e);    # TOML pointer
    var body = cyml_entry_body(e);     # markdown pointer

    # Convenience for single-entry files:
    cyml_split(data, len, &hdr, &hdr_len, &body, &body_len);

Zero-copy parser — returns pointers into the input buffer.
22-assertion test suite.

[[entries]]
name = "cyrius_cyml_manifest"
description = "cyrius.cyml — project manifest. Top-level package + build + release + deps blocks."
category = "cyrius"
---
Every Cyrius project carries a `cyrius.cyml` at the repo root.
Pure CYML; the file-level header (above any `[[entries]]`) is
the manifest. No `[[entries]]` block is used here — the manifest
is single-entry.

== TOP-LEVEL BLOCKS ==

    [package]
    name        = "myapp"
    version     = "${file:VERSION}"   # interpolation
    description = "..."
    license     = "GPL-3.0-only"
    repository  = "https://github.com/..."

    [build]
    src    = "src/main.cyr"
    output = "build/myapp"

    [release]
    bins        = ["myapp", "myapp-cli"]
    cross_bins  = ["myapp_aarch64"]
    scripts     = ["scripts/install.sh"]

    cyrius = "5.8.27"     # MINIMUM compiler version (v5.6.x+)

    [deps]
    stdlib = ["syscalls", "string", "alloc", "str", ...]

    [deps.<name>]
    git     = "https://github.com/MacCracken/<name>.git"
    tag     = "X.Y.Z"
    modules = ["dist/<name>.cyr"]

== INTERPOLATION ==

  ${file:PATH}       — read PATH (relative to manifest), trim
                       trailing whitespace. Used for VERSION.
  ${env:NAME}        — environment variable.
  ${file:foo:default} — file with default if missing.

== `cyrius` MINIMUM-VERSION CHECK ==

`cyrius build` reads the top-level `cyrius` field and refuses to
compile if the installed toolchain is older. Same pattern as
Rust's `rust-version`, Go's `go` directive, Zig's
`minimum_zig_version`. Bump when:

  - Using a new language feature (slices, multi-width types, etc.)
  - Using a new stdlib module that wasn't in earlier releases
  - Using a new compiler directive
  - Hitting a bug fix in a specific patch release

== `[release]` LISTS ==

`bins` / `cross_bins` / `scripts` are the SINGLE source of truth
for what the release pipeline ships. `release.yml`, `install.sh`,
and `cbt/pulsar.cyr` all read from this manifest — no list is
duplicated across multiple files. Adding a new binary requires
exactly one edit (here).

== `[deps]` AUTO-PREPEND ==

`stdlib = [...]` lists module bare-names (`syscalls`, not
`lib/syscalls.cyr`); `cyrius` auto-prepends each as
`include "lib/<name>.cyr"` to bundled source for
build/test/bench/fuzz/check/soak/smoke. Avoids repeating include
lines in every test/bench file.

`[deps.<name>]` blocks declare git-resolved deps. Materialized
into `lib/<name>_<basename>.cyr` (namespaced). Lockfile at
`cyrius.lock` records resolved SHAs.

[[entries]]
name = "object_directive"
description = "object; — emit ELF .o relocatable output (kernel_mode = 3)"
category = "cyrius"
---
`object;` at the top of a .cyr file triggers ELF .o relocatable
output (sets `kernel_mode = 3`). The compiler emits a proper
ELF object with sections:

  .text, .data, .rodata, .symtab, .strtab, .rela.text

Functions become `STT_FUNC`/`STB_GLOBAL` symbols. Fixup entries
convert to relocations:

  type 0 (var addr)     → R_X86_64_64 against .data
  type 1 (string addr)  → R_X86_64_64 against .rodata
  type 2 (fn call)      → R_X86_64_PC32 against function symbol
  type 3 (fn pointer)   → R_X86_64_64 against function symbol

PIC codegen for `object;` mode uses `LEA [rip+disp32]` +
`R_X86_64_PC32` relocs — eliminates `DT_TEXTREL` (glibc 2.38+
refuses `dlopen` of TEXTREL binaries).

Top-level code (enum values, global var inits) wraps in a
callable `_cyrius_init` function that C launchers must invoke
before any application function.

[[entries]]
name = "compiler_env_vars"
description = "Compile-time env vars — target selection, IR pipeline, regalloc, profiling"
category = "cyrius"
---
cycc reads several `CYRIUS_*` environment variables at startup
to switch target / enable optimizations / dump diagnostics.
Default-off — set at compile time, no source-code annotation
needed.

== TARGET SELECTION ==

  CYRIUS_TARGET_WIN=1     Windows PE32+ output (cycc native)
  CYRIUS_MACHO=1          Mach-O x86_64 output
  CYRIUS_MACHO_ARM=1      Mach-O aarch64 output
  CYRIUS_TARGET_AGNOS=1   AGNOS ring-3 userspace ABI (v6.0.x)

Cross-compile dispatch hooks. `cyrius build --aarch64` sets
target via the appropriate cross-compiler binary; the env vars
are mostly used by the cross-compiler binaries themselves.

== CODEGEN MODE ==

  CYRIUS_PIE=1           Position-independent codegen (ET_DYN,
                         ASLR-able). Mirrors the --pie flag. x86_64
                         RIP-relative + aarch64 adrp/add. (v6.1.6/.8)

== TS/TSX → JS EMIT (--emit-js) ==

  CYRIUS_JSX_PRAGMA=NAME Override the JSX lowering pragma (default
                         `h`). When set, the standalone `h` runtime
                         prelude is suppressed (the consumer supplies
                         its own pragma runtime, e.g. React.createElement).
                         (v6.1.11)

== IR PIPELINE ==

  CYRIUS_IR (unset)  IR off (default — emit raw bytes via E*/E3*)
  CYRIUS_IR=1        IR recording on, raw emit also runs in parallel
  CYRIUS_IR=2        IR recording + BB construction (no opt passes)
  CYRIUS_IR=3        IR + opt passes (LASE + const-fold + bitmap-
                     liveness DCE + DSE + fixed-point driver) +
                     codebuf patching of eliminated nodes

  CYRIUS_DCE_CAP=N   Bisection cap — kill at most N IR nodes via DCE
  CYRIUS_DSE_CAP=N   Bisection cap — kill at most N IR nodes via DSE

DCE/DSE caps help bisect codegen-vs-IR divergence: start
unbounded, narrow to the first cap that introduces the bug.
The opt passes only run under CYRIUS_IR=3; the lower modes are
recording-only diagnostics.

== REGALLOC PEEPHOLE (v5.6.20+) ==

  CYRIUS_REGALLOC_AUTO_CAP=N   Auto-enable picker for first N fns only
                               (-1 = uncapped, default; 0 = picker off)
  CYRIUS_REGALLOC_DUMP=1       Per-fn interval dump for picker debug
  CYRIUS_REGALLOC_PICKER_CAP=N Cap total assignments per fn (bisection)

The post-body peephole assigns up to 5 callee-saved regs
(rbx, r12-r15) to hot user-locals via Poletto-Sarkar linear-scan.
Bars `&local` slots from assignment via the safety scan. v5.8.16
§8 highlights the picker's interaction with slice high-half
slots — see field_notes/compiler/v5_8.

== DIAGNOSTICS ==

  CYRIUS_PROF=1    Per-fn compile-time profiling
  CYRIUS_STATS=1   Final stats dump (token count, fn count,
                   fixup count, code+data sizes, alloc usage)

== PIN DRIFT (v5.11.57) ==

  CYRIUS_NO_WARN_PIN_DRIFT=1   Suppress the cycc-side warning
                               that fires when cwd's
                               `cyrius.cyml [package].cyrius`
                               pin doesn't match cycc's
                               compile-time version. Default:
                               warning enabled.

  CYRIUS_STRICT_PIN=1          Upgrade pin-drift warning to a
                               hard exit (code 1) with
                               `error: cyrius.cyml pins X.Y.Z
                               but cycc is X.Y.W — toolchain
                               drift (CYRIUS_STRICT_PIN)`. CI
                               gating path. `cyrius build
                               --strict-pin` sets this for the
                               cycc child automatically.

  Both detect via the new `_check_cyml_pin_drift()` in
  `src/frontend/lex.cyr`. Surface drift regardless of wrapper
  state — the iron-boot papercut filing 2026-05-16 found that
  `~/.cyrius/bin/cyrius` had been frozen at .25-embedded since
  2026-05-12 (install.sh `_rebuild_stale` missed
  `version_str.cyr` transitive dep), and consumers saw `cyrius
  --version: 5.11.25` even when pinning .55+. cycc IS current
  per self-host discipline, so cycc-side detection bypasses the
  stale wrapper.

== DCE (v5.11.x) ==

  CYRIUS_DCE=1            NOP-fill detected-dead fn bodies (in-
                          place; binary size unchanged, just
                          replaced bytes). Off by default; the
                          dead-fn DETECTION runs always and
                          produces `note: N unreachable fns (M
                          bytes — set CYRIUS_DCE=1 to
                          eliminate, ...)`.
  CYRIUS_DCE_VERBOSE=1    Per-fn `  dead: <name>` list.

  Both arches (x86 + aarch64) since v5.11.59 — aarch64 gained
  the DCE pass + filter same slot. See `field_notes/compiler/
  retros/` for the cross-arch parity arc.

[[entries]]
name = "compiler_flags"
description = "cycc + cyrius command-line flags — --strict, --pie, --version, the TS modes (--lex-ts/--parse-ts/--emit-js), --aarch64, etc. (binary renamed cc5 → cycc at v6.0.0)."
category = "cyrius"
---
== cycc BINARY FLAGS == (the compiler binary; cc5 was its pre-v6.0.0 name)

  --version          Print "cycc X.Y.Z\n" and exit 0
  --strict           Refuse to emit a binary if any function
                     reference is undefined. Without --strict,
                     undefined-fn references warn but produce a
                     binary that SIGILLs (exit 132) when the call
                     is reached. RECOMMENDED for CI.

      Output on undef:
          error: --strict: refusing to emit binary with N undefined function(s)

  --pie              Position-independent codegen — ET_DYN, ASLR-able
                     (x86_64 RIP-relative `lea`; aarch64 `adrp`/`add`).
                     Also via CYRIUS_PIE=1 env. (v6.1.6 x86 / v6.1.8 aarch64.)

  TS/TSX FRONTEND MODES (take a `.ts`/`.tsx` path arg, else read stdin):
  --lex-ts [file]    Lex only; exit 0 (clean) / 1 (lex error).
  --parse-ts [file]  Lex + parse; exit 0 (both clean) / 1.
  --emit-js [file]   Lex + parse + emit JS to stdout (v6.1.11): strips
                     types/interfaces/aliases/`as`/generics, lowers JSX
                     to an `h()` pragma (CYRIUS_JSX_PRAGMA, default `h`,
                     + a standalone runtime prelude when JSX present),
                     ESM passthrough with type-only export pruning.
                     Exits non-zero on an AST-walk integrity failure.

  CLI parsing: cycc reads `/proc/self/cmdline` and walks every arg,
  matching by prefix — `--st` strict, `--ve` version, `--pie`,
  `--le` lex-ts, `--pa` parse-ts, `--em` emit-js. For the TS modes
  the next non-flag arg is the input path; otherwise cycc reads
  source on stdin.

== `cyrius build` FLAGS ==

  --aarch64          Use cycc_aarch64 cross-compiler
  --no-deps          Skip dep auto-prepend (compile only the
                     given source against bare stdlib)
  -D NAME            Inject `#define NAME` at top of bundled
                     source (feature-flag style)
  -v / --verbose     Show resolved compiler path + bundled-source
                     temp file path
  -q / --quiet       Suppress non-error stderr output

== `cyrius check` FLAGS ==

  --with-deps        Include `[deps]` distfiles in the syntax
                     check (default: standalone)

== `cyrius fmt` / `cyrius lint` / `cyrius doc` FLAGS ==

  --check            Exit-code-only mode — non-zero on drift,
                     silent on no-drift (matches Rust/Go fmt
                     conventions; aligned at v5.8.x cycle).
                     Suitable for CI gates.

== `cyrlint` FLAGS (the linter) ==

  --strict           Exit 2 if any warning is present (CI gate).
  --exit-with-count  Exit code = warning count (legacy; opt-in).
  --strict-deferrals Exit 2 if any UNTRACKED deferral-language
                     marker is present (v6.0.63). cyrlint flags
                     deferred / broken-work markers — TODO, FIXME,
                     SCAFFOLD, NOT_IMPLEMENTED, deferred, "for
                     now", "not yet", "follow-up", "out of scope",
                     ... — that are NOT cross-referenced by a
                     CHANGELOG / issue / roadmap / version pointer
                     on the same line. These use a SEPARATE counter
                     from warnings (so the legacy backlog doesn't
                     break the existing --strict gate); the count +
                     per-line notes go to STDERR (stdout's last line
                     stays "<n> warnings" for `tail -1` parsers),
                     non-failing by default. --strict-deferrals is
                     the hardening switch to flip once the backlog
                     is cross-referenced. Stops deferred work
                     rotting untracked in comments. `#skip-lint` on
                     a line exempts it from all rules.

== `cyrius doc` ADDITIONAL ==

  --serve [port]     Serve generated HTML docs locally on
                     `lib/http_server.cyr` (default port 8080).

== `cyrius api-surface` FLAGS ==

  --update           Regenerate `docs/api-surface.snapshot` from
                     current source. No flag → diff against
                     committed snapshot, exit 1 on drift.
  --snapshot=PATH    Diff against an alternate snapshot file.

== `cyrius capacity` FLAGS ==

  --check            Exit non-zero on cap overflow — for CI gates
  --json             Machine-readable output

== `cyrius deps` FLAGS ==

  --no-lock          Don't write/check cyrius.lock
  --verify           Verify lockfile SHAs match resolved tags;
                     exit non-zero on mismatch

[[entries]]
name = "lsp_and_plugins"
description = "cyrius-lsp + .lsp.json + MacCracken/cyrius-plugins marketplace"
category = "cyrius"
---
== `cyrius-lsp` (Language Server) ==

JSON-RPC 2.0 over stdin/stdout. Source at
`programs/cyrius-lsp.cyr`. Built via `cyrius lsp` →
`~/.cyrius/bin/cyrius-lsp`. Promoted to `[release].bins` at
v5.7.39.

Capabilities (current):
  initialize                    — handshake
  textDocument/didOpen          — compile + return diagnostics
  textDocument/didChange        — recompile + return diagnostics
  textDocument/didSave          — recompile + return diagnostics
  textDocument/definition       — cross-file go-to-def (v5.7.39)
  textDocument/documentSymbol   — symbol outline (v5.7.39)
  shutdown                      — exit cleanly

Diagnostics are produced by invoking cycc on the buffer and
parsing `error:<file>:<line>: <msg>` output back into LSP
`Diagnostic` records.

== `.lsp.json` (project-root manifest) ==

Editor-agnostic shape (same as gopls' `.lsp.json` convention).
Maps file extensions to language servers:

    {
      "cyrius": {
        "command": "cyrius-lsp",
        "args": [],
        "extensionToLanguage": {
          ".cyr":   "cyrius",
          ".tcyr":  "cyrius",
          ".bcyr":  "cyrius",
          ".fcyr":  "cyrius",
          ".scyr":  "cyrius",
          ".smcyr": "cyrius"
        }
      }
    }

Don't drop this file into each Cyrius repo — install the plugin
instead (next section). Per-repo `.lsp.json` was the original
wiring; the plugin extracts it to user scope.

== `MacCracken/cyrius-plugins` (Claude Code marketplace) ==

Sibling repo to `MacCracken/cyrius`. Houses the Claude Code
plugin manifests (`.claude-plugin/marketplace.json` +
`plugins/cyrius-lsp/`) so editor wiring lives outside the
language repo.

Install once at user scope:

    /plugin marketplace add MacCracken/cyrius-plugins
    /plugin install cyrius-lsp@cyrius-plugins

Tags follow `<plugin-name>--v<X.Y.Z>` convention (e.g.
`cyrius-lsp--v0.1.0`). Per-plugin tags so plugins version
independently. CI in the plugins repo runs `claude plugin
validate` + cross-checks marketplace.json ↔ plugin.json
version agreement on every PR; release.yml fires on tag push,
publishes a GitHub Release with auto-notes.

[[entries]]
name = "helper_scripts"
description = "cyriusly + cyrius-init.sh + cyrius-port.sh + cyrius-watch.sh + cyrius-repl.sh + cyrius-prompt-info"
category = "cyrius"
---
Shell scripts that wrap cycc / `cyrius` for common workflows.
Listed in cyrius.cyml's `[release].scripts`.

== `cyriusly` — toolchain orchestration + status ==

The Swiss-army-knife wrapper. Sub-commands:

  cyriusly setup              Install ~/.cyrius/bin to PATH;
                              symlink toolchain binaries; ensure
                              cycc / cyrius / cyrius-lsp resolvable
  cyriusly status             Print installed binaries + versions
  cyriusly upgrade            Pull + rebuild from main
  cyriusly nightly            Soak loop + bench history snapshot

Also drops a starship.toml / p10k snippet so the shell prompt
shows the current Cyrius project's version + dep status. Glyph:
🌀 (cyclone) for cyrius, ॐ (Om) for packages.

== `cyrius-init.sh` — project scaffold ==

Invoked as `cyrius init <name>`. Creates `<name>/` with:
  cyrius.cyml          (manifest skeleton)
  src/main.cyr         (hello-world entry)
  tests/tcyr/          (auto-discovered test dir)
  benches/             (bench dir)
  docs/development/    (roadmap / state / completed-phases stubs)
  README.md / VERSION  (version-bump-friendly defaults)
  .lsp.json            (DEPRECATED — install cyrius-plugins instead)

== `cyrius-port.sh` — Rust → Cyrius migration ==

Invoked as `cyrius port <rust-project>`. Reads Cargo.toml +
src/, scaffolds equivalent cyrius.cyml + src/, surfaces a
migration playbook at `docs/development/migration-strategy.md`.
Doesn't auto-translate Rust → Cyrius (out of scope).

== `cyrius-watch.sh` — file watcher ==

Invoked as `cyrius watch [src] [out]`. Polls `*.cyr` files via
`find -newer` and recompiles on change. Defaults: `src/main.cyr`
→ `build/app`. Interval via `CYRIUS_WATCH_INTERVAL` env (default
1 second). Polling rather than inotify — simple, portable,
sufficient for dev workflows. Ctrl+C to stop.

== `cyrius-repl.sh` — expression REPL ==

Invoked as `cyrius repl`. Reads expressions on stdin, wraps each
in a minimal `fn main` template, compiles + runs, prints result.

== `cyrius-prompt-info` — shell-prompt status helper ==

Used by the cyriusly starship/p10k integration. Reads the
nearest cyrius.cyml + dep lockfile, emits a compact status
string for prompt rendering. Drops redundant "name (name)"
when project name == repo name (v5.8.1 polish).

[[entries]]
name = "release_pipeline"
description = "release.yml + install.sh + cbt/pulsar.cyr — driven by [release] in cyrius.cyml"
category = "cyrius"
---
The release pipeline reads `[release]` from `cyrius.cyml` —
single source of truth for what ships. Adding a new binary
requires exactly one edit (the `bins` array); release.yml,
install.sh, and pulsar all pick it up automatically.

== `release.yml` (GitHub Actions) ==

Triggers on tag push (`vX.Y.Z`). Builds:
  - x86_64 Linux: cycc + every binary in `[release].bins`
  - aarch64 Linux: cross-compiles each binary in `[release].cross_bins`
    via cycc_aarch64
  - Windows PE: cross-compiles cycc_win + tools (when wired)
  - macOS Mach-O: cross-compiles via cycc_macho_arm

Stages binaries under `$STAGE/bin/`; `cross_bins` go under
`$STAGE/bin/` alongside the native (cycc_aarch64 in same dir as
cycc). v5.8.2 fixed a stage-path drift where cycc_aarch64 went to
`$STAGE/` instead of `$STAGE/bin/`.

Tarballs uploaded to the GitHub Release page.

== `install.sh` ==

Curl-pipeable installer:
    curl -sSf https://raw.githubusercontent.com/MacCracken/cyrius/main/scripts/install.sh | sh

Detects host triple, downloads the matching tarball, extracts to
`~/.cyrius/<version>/`, symlinks `~/.cyrius/bin/*` to the latest
version. `cyriusly setup` runs after to put `~/.cyrius/bin` on
PATH and write the `.cyriusrc` profile snippet.

== `cbt/pulsar.cyr` ==

Internal toolchain build orchestrator. Invoked by `cyrius
pulsar` (mostly a maintainer-side verb). Cross-compiles
`build/cycc-native-aarch64` so users on ARM64 hardware can
self-host without a manual cross-compile pass.

The `cycc-native-aarch64` binary is committed to `build/`
(gitignored except this one + the prior-major seed; see CLAUDE.md
"build/ tracking policy").

[[entries]]
name = "audit_test_check_pipeline"
description = "scripts/check.sh + cyrius audit — the 64-gate full-validation pipeline"
category = "cyrius"
---
The validation pipeline runs in three layers:

== LAYER 1 — `scripts/check.sh` (CI-grade, 64 gates at v5.8.19) ==

The repo's primary acceptance gate. Runs end-to-end and reports
N/M with each gate as PASS / FAIL / SKIP. Categories:

  - Build verifies: cycc compiles, cycc_aarch64 cross compiles,
    cycc_cx bytecode roundtrip, Mach-O cross, PE cross
  - Self-host verifies: byte-identical two-step + three-step
  - Heap map: 0 region overlaps, structure intact
  - Test suite: every tests/tcyr/*.tcyr (105 files at v5.8.19)
  - Format: cyrfmt --check on stdlib + src
  - Lint: cyrlint --check on stdlib + src
  - api-surface: snapshot drift detection (re-enables at v5.8.42)
  - Capacity: each cap (frame, heap, code, fixup) within budget
  - Topic-grouped TS suite: lex_combined / parse_core /
    parse_decls / parse_advanced
  - Per-feature regression scripts: regression-*.sh

== LAYER 2 — `cyrius audit` (dev-loop driver) ==

Runs the same set as a single command. Suitable for `pre-commit`
hook + post-feature verification. Aborts on first FAIL.

== LAYER 3 — `cyrius soak [N]` (long-running) ==

Wraps check.sh in N iterations + walks tests/scyr/*.scyr.
Catches non-determinism and codegen drift across runs.

== CLOSEOUT-PASS DISCIPLINE ==

CLAUDE.md "Closeout Pass (before every minor/major bump)"
defines the 11-step protocol that runs at the end of each
minor cycle. Mechanical (1-3) → judgment-call (4-8) → compliance
(9-10) → docs (11). Self-host break short-circuits the chain.

[[entries]]
name = "minimum_compiler_version_pin"
description = "`cyrius` field in cyrius.cyml — pin a minimum compiler version, error early if older"
category = "cyrius"
---
`cyrius.cyml` supports a top-level `cyrius` field specifying the
minimum compiler version a project requires. `cyrius build`
checks this and errors early if the installed toolchain is older
than declared.

USAGE:

    cyrius = "5.8.27"        # minimum compiler version

PATTERN: same shape as Rust's `rust-version`, Go's `go`
directive in go.mod, Zig's `minimum_zig_version` in build.zig.zon.

WHEN TO BUMP YOUR PROJECT'S MINIMUM:
  - Using a new language feature (slices, multi-width types,
    dot-syntax field access on Str / slice locals, etc.)
  - Using a new stdlib module that wasn't in earlier releases
    (e.g. `lib/random.cyr`, `lib/security.cyr` from v5.7.35;
    `lib/test.cyr` from v5.7.43; slice-typed wrappers from v5.8.18)
  - Using a new compiler directive (`#ifplat`, `#regalloc`,
    `#must_use`, `#derive`)
  - Hitting a bug fix in a specific patch release (e.g.
    16-byte fn-local layout-flip needed v5.8.16+)

`${file:VERSION}` interpolation works in `cyrius.cyml`, so a
project with its own VERSION file can avoid duplicating the
literal — vidya itself uses this pattern.

The minimum-version check fires at `cyrius build` time before
parse, so the error message is clear ("requires cyrius >= X.Y.Z;
have Y.X.Z") instead of failing later with a syntax error on
something the older parser doesn't understand.

[[entries]]
name = "cyriusly_native_port_v51110"
description = "cyriusly — toolchain-version management CLI, native cyrius port of scripts/cyriusly at v5.11.10"
category = "cyrius"
---
`cyriusly` is the user-facing CLI for switching between
installed cyrius toolchain versions. v5.11.10 closed the
shell-script → cyrius native port — `programs/cyriusly.cyr`
compiles to a binary in `[release].bins`. The bash script
`scripts/cyriusly` remains as a backend for `setup` /
`cmdtools` verbs that shell out to OS tools.

== INSTALL / UNINSTALL / UPDATE ==

  cyriusly install <version>     — fetch + extract binary
                                   release to ~/.cyrius/versions/<v>/
  cyriusly uninstall <version>   — remove ~/.cyrius/versions/<v>/
  cyriusly update                — check GitHub for newer version
                                   (curl GitHub API; no telemetry)

== VERSION SWITCH ==

  cyriusly use <version>         — set ~/.cyrius/current → <version>
                                   (POST-v5.11.25: writes cyrius.cyml's
                                   [package].cyrius field by default;
                                   --global flag for the legacy global
                                   pointer write)
  cyriusly use                   — print the resolved version + source
                                   (cyml-pinned / global / latest fallback)

== INFO ==

  cyriusly version               — print active toolchain version
  cyriusly list                  — list installed versions
  cyriusly ls                    — alias for list
  cyriusly which                 — print active binary path
  cyriusly home                  — print CYRIUS_HOME (~/.cyrius/)
  cyriusly help                  — verb list

== SETUP / CMDTOOLS ==

  cyriusly setup                 — shell out to scripts/cyriusly (
                                   shell aliases + completions install)
  cyriusly cmdtools              — shell out to scripts/cyriusly (
                                   develop-mode helper bins)

== INTERACTION WITH cyrius.cyml ==

Pre-v5.11.17, `cyrius deps` resolved stdlib_dir from the global
~/.cyrius/lib symlink — meaning `cyriusly use <other>` from a
sibling agent could wipe in-flight lib/ edits via the snapshot-
ping-pong loop. v5.11.17 fix: deps resolution prefers ./lib (for
the cyrius source repo) then `~/.cyrius/versions/<cyml-pinned>/
lib` (for downstream consumers) before the legacy global. See
`cyrius_deps_global_symlink_wedge_v51117` field note.

== COMPILED BINARY ==

`programs/cyriusly.cyr` → `~/.cyrius/bin/cyriusly` (~90 KB).
Heavy verbs (install / update / uninstall / setup / cmdtools)
use `exec_cmd` to shell out where the operation is fundamentally
shell-shaped (tarball extraction, curl downloads). Light verbs
(version / list / which / home / help / use) are full native.
